In the standard Ehrenfest description for electron–radiation dynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "subotnik_augmented_2010,li_mixed_2018"

\end_inset

, the electronic system is described by the electronic density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and the EM field described classically, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{E}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Here, we use a bar function to indicate the EM field under Ehrenfest dynamics.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
density matrix - Liouville
\end_layout

\end_inset

The electronic density matrix evolves following Liouville equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}}\left(\bar{\mathbf{E}},\bar{\mathbf{B}}\right),\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\right].\label{eq:liouville_rho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the so-called electronic Hamiltonian that depends only parametrically
 on the EM field is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}}\left(\bar{\mathbf{E}},\bar{\mathbf{B}}\right)=\widehat{H}_{s}-\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\bar{\mathbf{E}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right),\label{eq:electronic_Hamiltonian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we use the dipole approximation for the electron–field coupling.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
EM field - Maxwell
\end_layout

\end_inset

The EM field is governed by Maxwell's equation for classical electrodynamics
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\bar{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & -\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\bar{\mathbf{E}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right),\label{eq:maxwell_BE}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\bar{\mathbf{E}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & c^{2}\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\bar{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\bar{\mathbf{J}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right),\label{eq:maxwell_EB}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the current is generated by the averaged polarization
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\bar{\mathbf{J}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\bar{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right),\\
\bar{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & \text{Tr}_{s}\left\{ \widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right\} .\label{eq:polarization_mean}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The displacement is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{D}}=\epsilon_{0}\bar{\mathbf{E}}+\bar{\mathbf{P}}$
\end_inset

 in Ehrenfest dynamics, so that Maxwell's equation can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\bar{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & -\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\bar{\mathbf{D}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)+\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\bar{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right),\label{eq:maxwell_BD}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\bar{\mathbf{D}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & \frac{1}{\mu_{0}}\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\bar{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right).\label{eq:maxwell_DB}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which is equivalent to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
