Our current prescription of Ehrenfest+R dynamics has several advantages.
 First, it conserves the total electrodynamics energy.
 Second, since the system transition is effectively continuous and the stochasti
c EM field transition is minimal in magnitude, it is numerically stable.
 Third, the cost of each Ehrenfest+R trajectory is of the same order magnitude
 as the standard Ehrenfest dynamics, and it is easy to reach convergence.
 We note that the success of our prescription relies on the fact that the
 spontaneous emission follows Fermi's golden rule.
 Therefore, applying Ehrenfest+R method to other problems requires further
 modification of the current prescription.
 Namely, the framework pave the way for possible varieties of mixed quantum-clas
sical methods derived from the analysis of the electrodynamical QCLE and
 Ehrenfest EOM.
